</table>

<h2>1.6 Organization of the Report</h2>
<p>This report is organized into five chapters. <strong>Chapter 1</strong> introduces the project, its objectives, and the development timeline. <strong>Chapter 2</strong> surveys existing solutions and identifies gaps. <strong>Chapter 3</strong> presents the system design, including architecture diagrams, data flow, and database schema. <strong>Chapter 4</strong> discusses the implementation results and validation testing. <strong>Chapter 5</strong> concludes the report and outlines future enhancements.</p>

<!-- CHAPTER 2: LITERATURE SURVEY -->
<div class="pb"></div>
<h1 class="ct">Chapter 2<br>Literature Survey</h1>

<h2>2.1 Existing Solutions</h2>
<p>The current landscape of Indian ethnic wear e-commerce is dominated by platforms such as Nykaa Fashion, Myntra, and specialized boutique stores built on Shopify or WooCommerce. A review of these platforms reveals several architectural and experiential shortcomings:</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Nykaa Fashion &amp; Myntra:</strong> While these platforms offer a vast inventory, their UI is designed for mass-market appeal with information-dense layouts. The luxury narrative is diluted by adjacent product advertisements and promotional banners, which is antithetical to the aspirational positioning of high-end couture.</li>
<li><strong>Shopify-based Boutique Stores:</strong> Boutiques using SaaS platforms benefit from rapid deployment but are constrained by template limitations. Deep customization of checkout flows, search algorithms, and performance optimizations requires expensive third-party apps or custom plugins, leading to vendor lock-in.</li>
<li><strong>Custom-built Platforms:</strong> Brands like Sabyasachi and Tarun Tahiliani employ fully custom solutions, but these require significant development investment and dedicated engineering teams, making them inaccessible to smaller luxury labels.</li>
</ul>

<h2>2.2 Gap Analysis</h2>
<p>A comparative analysis of the surveyed platforms reveals the following critical gaps:</p>
<table>
<tr><th>Parameter</th><th>Mass-Market Platforms</th><th>SaaS Templates</th><th>SHREE (Proposed)</th></tr>
<tr><td>Performance (LCP)</td><td>&gt; 4s</td><td>&gt; 3s</td><td>&lt; 1.5s</td></tr>
<tr><td>Custom Authentication</td><td>Limited</td><td>Plugin-based</td><td>JWT + Firebase OAuth</td></tr>
<tr><td>Architecture</td><td>Monolithic</td><td>Monolithic</td><td>Decoupled (SPA + API)</td></tr>
<tr><td>Luxury UX/Branding</td><td>Generic</td><td>Template-constrained</td><td>Fully bespoke</td></tr>
<tr><td>Cost of Ownership</td><td>High (commissions)</td><td>Medium (subscriptions)</td><td>Low (self-hosted)</td></tr>
</table>

<h2>2.3 Proposed Solution</h2>
<p>SHREE Collective proposes a fully decoupled, open-source architecture using the MERN stack (MongoDB, Express.js, React 19, Node.js). This approach offers the following advantages:</p>
<ol>
<li><strong>Performance:</strong> React&rsquo;s virtual DOM and Vite&rsquo;s HMR ensure sub-second renders. IntersectionObserver defers heavy assets until they enter the viewport.</li>
<li><strong>Security:</strong> JWT tokens with httpOnly considerations, bcrypt with 12 salt rounds for password hashing, and role-based access control provide enterprise-grade security.</li>
<li><strong>Scalability:</strong> The decoupled architecture allows the frontend and backend to scale independently, and MongoDB&rsquo;s horizontal sharding supports future data growth.</li>
<li><strong>Customizability:</strong> Full code ownership eliminates vendor lock-in, enabling bespoke features such as the mega-menu navigation, custom inquiry forms, and artisan showcase sections.</li>
</ol>

<!-- CHAPTER 3: DESIGN FLOW -->
<div class="pb"></div>
<h1 class="ct">Chapter 3<br>Design Flow / Process</h1>

<h2>3.1 System Architecture</h2>
<p>The system employs a classic <strong>3-Tier Architecture</strong> consisting of the Presentation Tier (React SPA served by Vite), the Logic Tier (Express.js REST API on Node.js), and the Data Tier (MongoDB Atlas with Mongoose ODM). External cloud services&mdash;Firebase for OAuth authentication and Cloudinary for image asset management&mdash;are integrated via their respective SDKs and APIs.</p>

<p class="c"><strong>Table 3.1: Technology Stack Summary</strong></p>
<table>
<tr><th>Layer</th><th>Technology</th><th>Purpose</th></tr>
<tr><td>Frontend</td><td>React 19, Vite 6, CSS3</td><td>SPA UI, Routing, State Management</td></tr>
<tr><td>Backend</td><td>Node.js, Express 5</td><td>REST API, Business Logic, Auth</td></tr>
<tr><td>Database</td><td>MongoDB Atlas, Mongoose</td><td>Data Persistence, Schema Validation</td></tr>
<tr><td>Auth</td><td>JWT, bcrypt, Firebase Auth</td><td>Token-based Sessions, OAuth 2.0</td></tr>
<tr><td>Media</td><td>Cloudinary</td><td>Image CDN, Transformations</td></tr>
<tr><td>Dev Tools</td><td>Git, GitHub, Morgan, dotenv</td><td>Version Control, Logging, Config</td></tr>
</table>

